--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHAT IS AND ISN'T PROVEN BY THE SIMULATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The simulation proves:
- The Dockability Margin correctly quantifies proximity to instability in the
  2D planar model with the estimated disturbance coefficients.
- The CBF safety filter prevents wall collision across 50 randomised initial
  conditions in that same 2D model.
- The progressive speed limiting keeps M from collapsing during deliberate
  approach — abort is genuinely a last resort, not a routine event.
- The state machine transitions are correct and hysteresis prevents chattering.

The simulation does NOT prove:
- That the disturbance model is accurate. c0, c1, c2 are estimates. Phase 3
  system identification will replace them with measured values.
- That the 2D results transfer to 3D. Roll, yaw, and lateral wall effects are
  not modeled. Phase 3 extends to 3D.
- That the controller gains from simulation will work on real hardware. The
  real drone will have structural resonances, sensor noise, actuator lag, and
  communication delays that the simulation ignores.
- That the 200ms RK45 integration latency corresponds to real control loop
  latency. On the Jetson + PX4 stack the actual latency will differ and the
  abort trigger timing may need re-tuning.

